% Then, (ii) we show that the level sets of $R_1$ and $R_2$ must be equal to prevent neighbors of $\hat{f}$ making $R_1$ and $R_2$ gameable.
% Finally, this allows us to show that these level sets are equal at $\pi$ as well, and so $R_1$ and $R_2$ are equivalent.

\textbf{Step 1:}
First, because $\hat{\Pi}$ contains an open set, we can find some $\hat{\pi}$ such that $\hat{f} \doteq \mathcal{F}(\hat{\pi})$ is the center of an open ball.
Then, for small enough $\delta$, we have $\tilde{f} \doteq \hat{f} + \delta f$ and $\tilde{f'} \doteq \hat{f} + \delta f'$ are both inside this open ball.

\textbf{Step 2:}
%For any policy $\dot{\pi}$, define 
Let $\tilde{\pi}$ be the policy with visit counts $\tilde{f}$.
Consider the level sets $H_1, H_2$, defined as those policies with the same value of $\tilde{\pi}$ according to $\mathcal{R}_1$ or $\mathcal{R}_2$, respectively.
Note that if we consider reward functions as vectors in $\mathbb{R}^{|S||A|}$, then non-trivial reward functions have corresponding tangent planes, and these level sets are given by the intersection of these tangent planes with our policy set $\hat{\Pi}$.
