Now, if $H_1 \neq H_2$ we can find a point from within the open ball around $\tilde{f}$, that is above $H_1$ and below $H_2$, whose visit counts are realized by policy $\pi_{12}$.  This yielding $J_1(\pi_{12}) > J_1(\tilde{\pi})$ and $J_2(\pi_{12}) < J_2(\tilde{\pi})$, a contradiction.
Thus $H_1 = H_2$.

\textbf{Step 3:}
Since $H_1 = H_2$, we also have (considering $J \doteq \langle \mathcal{R}, \cdot \rangle$ as a function of visit counts) $J_2(\tilde{f}) = J_2(\tilde{f'})$. 
Expanding, we have: $J_2(\hat{f} + \delta f) = J_2(\hat{f} + \delta f')$, and thus by linearity we have $J_2(f) = J_2(f')$, i.e.\ 
$J_2(\pi) = J_2(\pi')$.
\end{proof}